==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Illation
<hw>Il*la"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>illatio</ets>, fr. <ets>illatus</ets>, used as p. p. of
<ets>inferre</ets> to carry or bring in, but from a different root: cf.
F. <ets>illation</ets>. See 1st <er>In-</er>, and <er>Tolerate</er>, and
cf. <er>Infer</er>.]</ety> <def>The act or process of inferring from
premises or reasons; perception of the connection between ideas; that
which is inferred; inference; deduction; conclusion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fraudulent deductions or inconsequent <qex>illations</qex> from a
false conception of things.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Illative</ent>⟦br⟧
